ğŸ”¹ React Data Binding
What is Data Binding?

Data binding means connecting data (state/props) with the UI, so when data changes, the UI updates automatically.

ğŸ“Œ React uses binding expressions {}

Example:
var name = "John";

<p>Hello! {name}</p>

<input type="text" value={name} />

Key Points:

JavaScript needs many DOM methods for binding

React handles binding efficiently

React supports one-way data binding by default

ğŸ”¹ One-Way vs Two-Way Binding
One-Way Binding (Default)

Data flows from state â†’ UI

UI cannot change data automatically

Two-Way Binding

Requires explicit implementation

Mostly done using onChange + useState

ğŸ”¹ Handling Data in React Components
Important Concepts:

React apps use HTTP protocol

HTTP is stateless

Data is not remembered between requests

âŒ Not recommended:

var name = "John"; // Bad practice


âœ” Recommended:

Use component local state

ğŸ”¹ Local State in React
What is Local State?

Data that belongs to one component

Created when component is created

Used to store dynamic data

ğŸ”¹ useState() Hook
What is a Hook?

Hook is predefined business logic

Provided by React

Used to access component state

useState() Definition
const [getter, setter] = useState(initialValue);


âœ” Uses destructuring
âœ” Returns:

Getter â†’ reads state

Setter â†’ updates state

Example:
const [price, setPrice] = useState(40);

ğŸ”¹ FAQ on useState()
1ï¸âƒ£ Can we use var or let for state?

âœ” Yes
âŒ Not recommended

2ï¸âƒ£ Why use const for state?

State should not allow reassignment

var / let allow reassignment

const protects state reference

3ï¸âƒ£ How can we update state if const is used?

âŒ Invalid:

setPrice = 50; // âŒ Not allowed


âœ” Valid:

setPrice(50); // âœ… Correct


ğŸ‘‰ State is updated through setter function, not assignment

ğŸ”¹ Summary

âœ” Bootstrap is enabled via npm & imports
âœ” React uses className, not class
âœ” Data binding uses {}
âœ” React supports one-way binding
âœ” Component data must be stored in state
âœ” useState() manages local state
